ce:section.ce:para:
It is well-known that the H2O2– pyrogallol produces a weak CL through energy transfer from (1O2*)2 to purpurogallin (PP), where (1O2*)2 is formed by the collision of peroxide species, and PP is pyrogallol oxidation intermediate product. The excited PP (PP*) emits light in the wavelength range of 470–510 nm (Fig. S2) [45,46]. As mentioned above, in the presence of both BNQDs and Co2+ the CL intensity is amplified about 2000-fold. For understanding the emitting species in this reaction, the CL spectrum of H2O2– pyrogallol -BNQD-Co2+ was recorded by a spectrofluorimeter. As can be observed from Fig. 4
                        , the obtained spectrum displays a peak with a maximum around 485 nm which is related to PP* [45]. The emission wavelength range of the H2O2-pyrogallol in the presence of individual BNQDs and Co2+, obtained by optical filters, was 470–550 nm, which indicates that in these systems, likewise, the emitting spices is PP*. The appearance of the peak around 400–450 nm in the UV–Vis spectrum of H2O2– pyrogallol-BNQD and H2O2– pyrogallol-Co2+ is the proof of the formation of PP (Fig. 5
                        ) [47,48]. When both BNQDs and Co2+ are added to H2O2– pyrogallol system the solution color changes obviously (inset of Fig. 5) and a great shift in the UV–Vis spectrum of the solution is observed (curve d in Fig. 5). We suspect that BNQDs and Co2+ form a complex. The appearance of a strong and broad peak in the UV–Vis spectrum (attributed to a charge transfer absorption) accompanying a distinct pink color of solution confirms the formation of the BNQD-Co2+ complex (Fig. S3). Our results show that this complex possesses a strong catalytic effect on the oxidation of pyrogallol by H2O2. This is evident from the CL time profiles in Fig. 3. As can be seen, in the presence of BNQDs/Co2+ the CL signal reaches its maximum within 2 s after injection of H2O2, while the rise time is 150 s for the system itself, and 3 s in the presence of only BNQDs, and 40 s in the presence of only Co2.

To procure the highest sensitivity, the influence of experimental variables including the concentration of H2O2, pyrogallol, Co2+, the amount of BNQDs and pH were inquired and results were presented in Fig. S6 (ESM). The optimum quantities are 400 µL BNQDs, 0.5 mM Co2+, 0.1 mM pyrogallol, and 50 mM H2O2. The effect of pH on the decreased CL intensity was investigated in the range of 3.0–8.0 using Britton–Robinson buffer. It was found that variation pH had no effect on the response. Under these conditions, the CL intensity of H2O2– pyrogallol-BNQD-Co2+ system decreases with increasing concentration of TFA (Fig. 6
                        ) and a linear logC- ΔI calibration plot in the 20 nM to 90 µM concentration range was obtained. The regression equation was ΔI = 43509logC + 82052, R2 = 0.995 (ΔI: difference between the CL intensity in the absence and presence of TFA, C: concentration of TFA in µM.), the limit of detection (LOD = 3sb/slope) and precision (RSD%) (n = 5, [TFA] = 0.1 µM) were 6.0 nM and 2.4%, respectively. The analytical characteristics of diverse methods for TFA are summarized in Table 1
                        . As can be seen, the performance of the proposed method is better than or comparable with most other methods and, besides, it is easy-operation, fast and inexpensive.
